('urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1',2,244,245,'\nSo spake Thersites, railing at Agamemnon, shepherd of the host.  But quickly to his side came goodly Odysseus,  and with an angry glance from beneath his brows, chid him with harsh words, saying:\"'),
('urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1',2,246,247,'\nSo spake Thersites, railing at Agamemnon, shepherd of the host.  But quickly to his side came goodly Odysseus,  and with an angry glance from beneath his brows, chid him with harsh words, saying:\"'),
('urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1',2,248,249,'Thersites of reckless speech, clear-voiced talker though thou art, refrain thee, and be not minded to strive singly against kings.  For I deem that there is no viler mortal than thou amongst all those that with the sons of Atreus came beneath Ilios.'),
('urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1',2,250,251,'  Wherefore \'twere well thou shouldst not take the name of kings in thy mouth as thou protest, to cast reproaches upon them, and to watch for home-going.'),
('urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1',2,252,253,'  In no wise do we know clearly as yet how these things are to be, whether it be for good or ill that we sons of the Achaeans shall return. Therefore dost thou now continually utter revilings against Atreus\' son, Agamemnon, shepherd of the host,  for that the Danaan warriors give him gifts full many; whereas thou pratest on with railings.'),
