('urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1',2,278,278,'  Never again, I ween, will his proud spirit henceforth set him on to rail at kings with words of reviling.\"'),
('urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1',2,278,279,'\nSo spake the multitude; but up rose Odysseus, sacker of cities, the sceptre in his hand, and by his side flashing-eyed Athene,  in the likeness of a herald, bade the host keep silence, that the sons of the Achaeans, both the nearest and the farthest, might hear his words, and lay to heart his counsel.'),
