('urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1',2,557,558,'  And with him there followed fifty black ships.\nAnd Aias led from Salamis twelve ships, and stationed them where the battalions of the Athenians stood.\nAnd they that held Argos and Tiryns, famed for its walls,  and Hermione and Asine, that enfold the deep gulf, Troezen and Eïonae and vine-clad Epidaurus, and the youths of the Achaeans that held Aegina and Mases,—these again had as leaders Diomedes, good at the war-cry, and Sthenelus, dear son of glorious Capaneus.'),
